+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EHKwoDNWrDv38KjRZ5nDZP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me design the approach:\n\n**Design Decisions (Autopilot):**\n\n**Q: Algorithm for solveToggle?**\n→ Choosing: Gaussian elimination over GF(2)\nReasoning: Each button press is a binary variable (press or not). Each light equation is XOR of button effects = target. This is a system of linear equations over GF(2). Gaussian elimination solves it in O(n²m) time, well within the 40×40 constraint.\n\n**Q: Algorithm for solveCounter?**\n→ Choosing: Gaussian elimination over GF(p)\nReasoning: Same structure but modular arithmetic. Since modulus is always prime, GF(p) is a field with multiplicative inverses. Standard Gaussian elimination works.\n\n**Q: How to find minimum presses / lexicographically smallest?**\n→ Choosing: After row reduction, enumerate free variables optimally\nReasoning: After Gaussian elimination, free variables (columns without pivots) can be set freely. For solveToggle, enumerate all 2^k combinations of free variables (k = number of free vars, at most 40 but typically small) and pick the solution with fewest 1s, then lexicographically smallest. For solveCounter, similarly enumerate p^k combinations of free variables. For large k, we need a smarter approach — but for the toggle case, with up to 40 buttons, k could be large. We need to handle this carefully.\n\n**Q: What if free variables make enumeration infeasible?**\n→ Choosing: For GF(2), use systematic search with pruning. For GF(p), use greedy approach for free variables.\nReasoning: For GF(2) with many free variables, we can iterate through possible counts of presses (starting from minimum possible) and find lexicographically smallest. For GF(p), we minimize total presses by trying each free variable value and computing dependent values, minimizing sum.\n\nLet me write the design document and then proceed to implementation."}],"stop